on Fridays round midnight.

166
00:16:34,568 --> 00:16:36,253
They do not. Do they, Mummy?

167
00:16:36,369 --> 00:16:38,770
Yes, you don't see them
cos you're asleep.

168
00:16:38,889 --> 00:16:41,540
Tonight's Friday,
as a matter of fact.

169
00:16:41,649 --> 00:16:44,812
But then you'd be
too bloody bored to see them.

170
00:16:44,929 --> 00:16:48,491
No, I'm not, Mummy.
I promise I won't be bored.

171
00:16:48,610 --> 00:16:52,012
- Even bloody bored?
- Promise!

172
00:16:52,130 --> 00:16:55,533
Well, if you're gonna be up
at midnight, get to bed now.

173
00:16:59,251 --> 00:17:02,495
- Say good night to everybody.
- Good night, everybody.

174
00:17:02,612 --> 00:17:07,779
- Do they really come, Mummy?
- Fairies only live in books.

175
00:17:07,893 --> 00:17:10,703
The Industrial Revolution
killed the fairies.

176
00:17:10,813 --> 00:17:13,180
They were left with nowhere to live.

177
00:17:13,293 --> 00:17:17,458
- Except our imaginations.
- Imaginations are a luxury.

178
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:21,777
- Beg your pardon?
- Most people can't afford them.

179
00:17:21,895 --> 00:17:25,104
I don't think imagination
is dependent on economics, is it?

180
00:17:25,215 --> 00:17:29,107
In a factory you're doing exactly
the same thing day after day.

181
00:17:29,216 --> 00:17:33,345
An active imagination is what allows
people to do that kind of work.

182
00:17:33,455 --> 00:17:36,063
Oh, well, you'd know, of course!

183
00:17:37,176 --> 00:17:40,737
I just think
that's what you'd have to do.

184
00:17:40,857 --> 00:17:43,508
You'd have to be imagining
other things.

185
00:17:43,617 --> 00:17:46,588
Please don't tell us
what the working <i>class</i> think,

186
00:17:46,698 --> 00:17:48,746
thanks very much.

187
00:18:03,820 --> 00:18:06,107
I think what the Bishop's
really hoping for

188
00:18:06,220 --> 00:18:08,905
is that we can come to a compromise,

189
00:18:09,020 --> 00:18:11,591
find some other examples
of your work.

190
00:18:11,700 --> 00:18:13,988
The great thing is no... Your chair.

191
00:18:14,101 --> 00:18:18,584
- No one wants to see you excluded.
- Now, that is a comfort.

192
00:18:18,701 --> 00:18:22,343
I hadn't realised the Church's
interest in contemporary painting.

193
00:18:22,462 --> 00:18:25,671
It's just The Crucified Venus
we're uncomfortable with.

194
00:18:28,063 --> 00:18:30,543
- Pooh?
- It's me.

195
00:18:30,663 --> 00:18:31,869
Come in.

196
00:18:34,864 --> 00:18:38,550
Poor old Piglet.
Pru gave you a bit of a working over.

197
00:18:38,664 --> 00:18:43,147
I'll survive.
Did you get anywhere with Mr Lindsay?

198
00:18:43,264 --> 00:18:46,474
He insists it's up to the public
to decide for themselves

199
00:18:46,585 --> 00:18:48,110
if they want to see his pictures.

200
00:18:48,225 --> 00:18:50,956
Of course, they have to see them
first to decide,

201
00:18:51,065 --> 00:18:53,511
by which time
the damage has been done,

202
00:18:53,626 --> 00:18:57,187
but that is a bit of logic
which is lost upon him. Never mind.

203
00:18:58,026 --> 00:19:01,110
I'll have another shot
in the morning before we go.

204
00:19:01,227 --> 00:19:04,549
Do you think the pictures
actually damage people?

205
00:19:05,427 --> 00:19:08,875
I think that the sexual ones
are just rather childish

206
00:19:08,988 --> 00:19:11,753
but I do think
negative images build up

207
00:19:11,868 --> 00:19:13,677
and don't any good in the long run

208
00:19:13,788 --> 00:19:18,431
and I think The Crucified Venus
is offensive and downright arrogant.

209
00:19:18,549 --> 00:19:20,438
- I'm coming, I'm coming!

210
00:19:21,309 --> 00:19:23,994
- Hurry up, stupid!
- I'm running as fast as I can,

211
00:19:24,109 --> 00:19:26,238
you disgusting thing!

212
00:19:26,350 --> 00:19:29,877
